               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1242" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1242" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1242" type="surname" value="STANTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1242" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM STANTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am other to John and Thomas Wheatley. On</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183702270186"></xptr>
               <p>the 15th of February last, at seven o'clock in the morning, I missed the bridle which I had seen in the stable the night before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1243" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1243" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1243" type="surname" value="BOLTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1243" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BOLTON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 166.) About half-past one o'clock on Friday morning, the 4th of February, I saw the prisoner come out of Messrs. Wheatleys' yard with something wrapped in the bottom of her gown—I asked what she had got—she said "Nothing," but I found this bridle—she said she had picked it up in the stable-yard.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I met a drunken man—he told me he was other there, and said be would treat me to something to drink, but he wanted to go down the yard first—I went down with him—he took down a bridle and gave it me, and began to pull me about—I slapped his face and ran away—an officer saw him—he heard me scream and then came down.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I had seen her and a man about that evening, but he did not go down the yard with her—she asked him to go down with her, but he would not—he left her and met me about twenty yards from the turning to the stable—I went on and met the prisoner with this bridle—she did not cry till I took her, and then she threw herself on the ground, and called out and said I was beating her.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
